{
  "text": "PCR and some ISHH studies providing evidence for significant D 1 -D 2 colocalization [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Although functionally significant D 1 -D 2 colocalization may occur in some striatal projection neurons, our EM immunolabeling indicates that the D 1 -immunolabeled and D 2 -immunolabeled spines in our sample primarily belonged to different striatal projection neuron populations, with under 10% of D 1 spines possessing D 2 and under 10% of D 2 spines possessing D 1 . In this light, our findings that the mean size of terminals making asymmetric synaptic contact with D 1 spines (0.45 m) was similar to that of IT-type terminals (0.41 Tables 2 and 3 , however, the IT-type terminals far more commonly contact D 1 than D 2 spines. \u03e9d, Labeled dendrites; \u03eat, unlabeled terminals; \u03e9t, labeled terminals. m), whereas the mean size of terminals making asymmetric synaptic contact with D 2 spines (0.61 m) was more similar to that of PT-type terminals (0.82 m) suggests, at the very least, that striato-EP-SNr neurons receive predominantly IT-type terminals, and striato-GP neurons receive many more PT-type terminals than do striato-EP-SNr neurons. The disparity between mean terminal size on D 2 \u03e9 spines and PT-type terminal size may not be as great as appears, because the mean size of PT-type terminals was less (0.70 m) in the current study combining spine immunolabeling with BDA terminal labeling than in our previous study of PT labeling alone (0.82 m) [CITATION_5] . Using the measured mean size of PT-type terminals in the current D 1 -and D 2 -immunolabeled tissue, it can be algebraically deduced from the size of the terminals on D 1 -immunolabeled spines that only 12.5% of the D 1 spines immunolabeled in our second line of study received PT-type input. This slight PT input to D 1 spines may reflect the existence of PT-recipient D 1 \u03e9 striato-GP neurons (possibly also possessing D 2 ), which would be consistent with reports that 10 -20% of striatal enkephalinergic neurons possess D 1 [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . The minor PT input to D 1 spines could also mean that some D 1 \u03e9 striatonigral neurons possess PT-recipient spines, which is consistent with our findings from our third line of study combining D 1 spine immunolabeling with BDA-labeling of PT-type terminals.",
  "correct_citation": {
